			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">By positioning the mob, I'm pretty sure that means that when the tank backs out of melee range, the mob follows.  I use this all the time when I'm MT on my warrior.  However, for this to work, tank aggro &gt;&gt; other melee aggro (including pets).
<br />

<br />
What I do as a mage, is when mob is out of postion, do /pet hold.  The mob will not follow pet through PC's and tank can then postion mob.  If pet has higher aggro than the tank, a taunt will get that aggro and then taking pet off makes postioning easier.
<br />

<br />
If you don't have /pet  hold, then it is alot more of a problem and you will need to go to water pet/taunt off.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
